{"questionId":"17629","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The Maxwell Ohm Company is designing a portable Bluetooth speaker. The speaker is in the&nbsp;shape of a cylinder with a hemisphere at each end of the cylinder.</p>\n<p><img style=\"display:block;margin-left:auto;margin-right:auto;\" src=\"__IMG__/dbcd221b4bb4d9c012b7a806f9934266848ede94.png\"></p>\n<p>The dimensions of the speaker, in centimetres, are illustrated in the following diagram where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi></math>&nbsp;is the radius of the hemisphere, and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>l</mi></math> is the length of the cylinder, with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>0</mn></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>l</mi><mo>≥</mo><mn>0</mn></math>.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/d80c74eb2795a9d1751de44a78ed4859ee9616d8.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The Maxwell Ohm Company has decided that the speaker will have a surface area of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>300</mn><mo> </mo><msup><mtext>cm</mtext><mn>2</mn></msup></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The quality of sound from the speaker will improve as <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>V</mi></math> increases.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Using your answer to part (d), show that <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>V</mi></math> is a maximum when <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi></math> is equal to&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msqrt><mfrac><mn>75</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi></mfrac></msqrt><mo> </mo><mtext>cm</mtext></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>150</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp; <strong>OR</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mtext>d</mtext><mi>V</mi></mrow><mrow><mtext>d</mtext><mi>r</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>&nbsp; <strong>OR</strong>&nbsp; sketch of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mtext>d</mtext><mi>V</mi></mrow><mrow><mtext>d</mtext><mi>r</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math>-intercept indicated&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/bde4c90012a9010dbb750a723c221f737136433a.png\"></p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Award <em><strong>(M1)</strong></em> for equating their derivative to zero or a sketch of their derivative with <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math>-intercept indicated.</p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mfrac><mn>150</mn><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi></mrow></mfrac></msqrt></math>&nbsp; <strong>OR</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>150</mn><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(A1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mfrac><mn>75</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi></mfrac></msqrt></math>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(AG)</strong></em></p>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> The <em><strong>(AG)</strong></em> line must be seen for the preceding <em><strong>(A1)</strong></em> to be awarded.</p>\n<p><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"17629","referenceCode":"19N.2.SL.TZ0.T_6e","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Using your answer to part (d), show that V is a maximum when r is equal to 75π cm.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"e","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 5—Calculus","Topic 5—Calculus","SL 5.3—Differentiating polynomials, n E Z","Topic 5—Calculus","SL 5.6—Stationary points, local max and min","Topic 5—Calculus","SL 5.7—Optimisation","Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.1—3d space, volume, angles, midpoints"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}